<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="547" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1366]" box="[151,799,690,715]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,690,715]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">Description.</emphasis>
Length (including wings): male 
<quantity box="[664,796,690,715]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" unit="mm" value="3.4" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="3.3">3.3–3.5mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1366]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Crown ochraceous; face mainly yellowish-white, lower part light ochraceous, anteclypeus and gena white, ocelli hazel (
<figureCitation box="[294,367,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1949,1971]" captionTargetBox="[192,1413,436,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,426,1938]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Busonia curvata sp. nov. A, habitus, dorsal view; B, habitus, lateral view; C, head and thorax, dorsal view; D, face. Busonia fusca sp. nov. E, habitus, dorsal view; F, habitus, lateral view; G, head and thorax, dorsal view; H, face. Busonia lactata sp. nov. I, habitus, dorsal view; J, habitus, lateral view; K, head and thorax, dorsal view; L, face." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Figs. 
<number box="[356,367,763,787]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
K, L). Pronotum and mesoscutum dark brown, lateral margin yellowish; scutellum light yellow. Forewing hyaline with brown tinge, broad band along costa except for a subapical semi-heart-shape, black (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1949,1971]" captionTargetBox="[192,1413,436,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,426,1938]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Busonia curvata sp. nov. A, habitus, dorsal view; B, habitus, lateral view; C, head and thorax, dorsal view; D, face. Busonia fusca sp. nov. E, habitus, dorsal view; F, habitus, lateral view; G, head and thorax, dorsal view; H, face. Busonia lactata sp. nov. I, habitus, dorsal view; J, habitus, lateral view; K, head and thorax, dorsal view; L, face." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,163,835,859]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
J). Mesepimeron brownish. Legs and hind leg macrosetae yellowish-white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1366]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Male genitalia. Pygofer broad, with height more than length. Appendage of segment X slender, at 
<number box="[1305,1315,874,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1325,1341,874,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="4.0">4</number>
th curved posteriorly, hook-like, in posterior view crossing over each other. Subgenital plate narrow, with a few hair-like seta on dorsal margin (
<figureCitation box="[363,432,945,970]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1671,1693]" captionTargetBox="[179,1404,182,1653]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[164,1422,169,1665]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Busonia lactata sp. nov. A, male pygofer, anal tube and subgenital plate, lateral view; B, connective, ventral view; C, style, lateral view; D, aedeagus, ventral view; E, aedeagus, lateral view. Busonia micrata sp. nov. F, aedeagus, ventral view; G, aedeagus, lateral view; H, male pygofer, anal tube and subgenital plate, lateral view; I, connective, ventral view; J, style, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241684/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Fig. 
<number box="[417,432,946,970]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Connective similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[732,893,945,969]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Busonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[732,893,945,969]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">Busonia fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[902,994,945,970]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[902,994,945,970]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
. Style with angular process and a few setae on ventral margin. Aedeagus dorsal margin broad, concave, shaft tapering apically in lateral view; shaft apex rounded, broadened subapically, compressed subbasally in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[968,1046,1017,1042]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1671,1693]" captionTargetBox="[179,1404,182,1653]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[164,1422,169,1665]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Busonia lactata sp. nov. A, male pygofer, anal tube and subgenital plate, lateral view; B, connective, ventral view; C, style, lateral view; D, aedeagus, ventral view; E, aedeagus, lateral view. Busonia micrata sp. nov. F, aedeagus, ventral view; G, aedeagus, lateral view; H, male pygofer, anal tube and subgenital plate, lateral view; I, connective, ventral view; J, style, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/241684/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
Figs. 
<number box="[1031,1046,1018,1042]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
D, E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,943,1053,1078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,690,1366]" box="[199,943,1053,1078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1053,1078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="547">Etymology.</emphasis>
